# Zener Diode

> [!word] Zener Diode
> A Zener diode is used to **stabilize a voltage source**
>
> - A zener diode is similar to a [[61-Archive/20220221170726-diode|diode]], but it also allows negative voltage to flow if it is larger than the [[61-Archive/20220413133445-breakdown-voltage|breakdown voltage]].

Allow [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]] to pass through when $$(V_{on}<V) || (V<V_{BD})$$

When $V_{on}<V$ --> The Zener Diode is **on**

When $V<V_{BD}$ --> The Zener Diode is **reversely on**

> [!note]
> When $V<|V_{BD}|$, the zener diode will clamp the [[61-Archive/20220318120826-voltage|voltage]] to $V_{BD}$ to protect the circuit. However, power will be wasted.

## Usage

### DC to DC Conversion

> [!example]
> When your phone needs 9V to operate, but the motion sensor only needs 5V, then you can insert [[61-Archive/20220221170305-battery|battery]], and use Zener diode to stabilize the voltage source

![../60-Meta-Attachments/8c9fd8f89941bd14242d729a93ed79d3.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Zener Diode must be connected reversely if we want to use its [[61-Archive/20220413133445-breakdown-voltage|Breakdown Voltage]]

Before the [[61-Archive/20220413133445-breakdown-voltage|Breakdown Voltage]] is reached:

$V_{z}=\frac{3}{4}V_{in}$
[[61-Archive/20220408120857-ohm's-law|Ohm's Law]]

![../60-Meta-Attachments/eef3b601b7da08b8644bf970fdd7888e.png](data:image/png;base64,)

When The [[61-Archive/20220413133445-breakdown-voltage|Breakdown Voltage]] is reached:

$V_{z}=V_{bd}$
![../60-Meta-Attachments/b0b6e192f3227b835702797bef7a2b16.png](data:image/png;base64,)

$$
\begin{align*}
\frac{3}{4}V_{in}&=5.7V\\

V_{in}&=7.6V

\end{align*}
$$

When $V_{in}$ is $7.6$ (in this particular case), $V_{z}=V_{bd}$, so the Zener diode starts working and the [[61-Archive/20220318120826-voltage|Voltage]] stabilizes

> [!tip]
> Since $100\ohm$ and (Zener diode and $300\ohm$) are in series. Their voltage  are in terms of ratio. So only $\frac{3}{4}$ of the initial $V_{in}$ will be provided to the zener diode. Further, the voltage given to the zener diode has to be $> V_{BD}$. Overall, the Voltage $V_{in}>\text{ratio of voltage given to zener diode}\times V_{BD}$

## Example Question

![../60-Meta-Attachments/4f449900e6d8de8deaf62fac932f0785.png](data:image/png;base64,)

$$5.6=\frac{500}{500+100}V_{in}$$
